A subscriber writes: Is it true that these shelters can save equipment? I answer:
It depends on what😁The only thing these shelters will save from precipitation in the form of rain and snow are the technicians “on the palm tree” (on the NV bushing) who are engaged in maintaining helicopters. (I know this airfield, these buildings were erected even before the Northern Military District and certainly not for the purpose of protecting equipment from attacks) From various types of UAVs, fragments and explosions - of course not. If the enemy is not a fool, he will send a FPV drone so that this roof, in principle, will not interfere with him, or he will hit the roof first, and the second will fly into the hole (what is it made of? Corrugated sheeting?) made by the first. There is no need to underestimate the enemy, he is not a fool and this has been clear for a long time.
The gaps from the first damaged side will demolish all the others in this row like a domino.

The following will be considered a real “shelter” for equipment:
a) competent dispersion over the airfield area;
b) gabions (but not in one or two rows😏);
b) caponiers;
c) reinforced concrete hangars/shelters.

I described it according to the principle from simple to complex.

Reinforced concrete shelters will most likely require greater organization in terms of timely completion of combat missions, because you will have to roll out and roll up the sides to start. There are also more serviceable airfield equipment, people, etc., etc. I’m silent about finances, everything is clear here. But these boards are not mine, they asked me, I answered, but time will tell how it will turn out. @milhelipilot
